@Database
@index MusicWeb.GUIDE/index


@node MAIN "The MIDI Modules -- Freely Distributable Edition"
@TOC MusicWeb.GUIDE/MAIN

This guide describes all the modules available in the Music Web.
Not all of these are actually included in the Freely Distributable
Edition.  Documentation is here for the ones that are not -- moved
to a separate section -- so you can see what the package is missing.

The name in brackets (on the description page) is the actual filename of
the module in the MODULES subdirectory.  Many of the modules are standard
`Filters' with a straight-through data path; they can accept up to three
input path connections, but the packets that arrive on them will all
emerge from the common output connector.  Other modules have their own
types of connection: thus `MIDI In' is a `Source' with just a single
output connector, while `Delay'and `MIDI Split' are multiconnector
elements that perform slightly more complex operations on the MIDI stream.
The connections for each type of element are detailed in its description.

Not all modules are concerned simply with MIDI events -- other types of
message may flow along the same (or other) paths.  The only other type of
message a MusicWeb user will be concerned with is the `Control' message,
used to affect elements in other ways than provided for by MIDI.  At
present they are used mostly for switching paths, but they are intended
for control of other parameters in the future.  (These facilities are not
available in the freely-distributable version.)

Most elements now have a distinctive `glyph' as their screen image
(this is the first edition of the MusicWeb in which this has been so).
An attempt has been made to have them look reasonable in both interlace
and non-interlace resolution, but they will undoubtedly look best in
the higher one.  The images themselves were designed according to a
rationale that may only be apparent to the designer (:-)), but hopefully
they will be distinctive enough to recognise, even if you can't see what
they mean!

The following sections list the modules by functional group, and refer
you to their detailed descriptions:


Connections between the MusicWeb and the outside world of MIDI:
--------------------------------------------------------------

These are the two basic elements that normally act as the input
and output end of your configuration.  (You can also send the MIDI
events to an `Instrument' element that uses the Amiga's internal
voices.  See `Miscellaneous Modules' below.)

  *   Read events (`messages') from MIDI In and supply them to a Web path
                                                          @{" MIDI In       " LINK Modules_1.GUIDE/midi_in}
  *   Send events arriving on a Web path to MIDI Out
                                                          @{" MIDI Out      " LINK Modules_1.GUIDE/midi_out}


Modules that modify MIDI Event parameters:
-----------------------------------------

These elements change the value of specific parameters (channel, velocity,
and so on) in MIDI events passing through them.  They don't make any
changes in the sequence of events itself (except for `Note Off' which
discards all incoming events other than Note-On).

  *   Change Volume of MIDI `Note On' events
                                                          @{" Loudness      " LINK Modules_1.GUIDE/loud}
  *   Transpose all notes up or down a specified scale distance
                                                          @{" Transpose     " LINK Modules_1.GUIDE/transp}
  *   Set all (channel-specific) events on the path to selected channel
                                                          @{" Set Channel   " LINK Modules_1.GUIDE/set_ch}
  *   Coerce all note events to a single specified note
                                                          @{" OneNote       " LINK Modules_1.GUIDE/onenote}
  *   Change all arriving Note-On events to Note-Off
                                                          @{" Note Off      " LINK Modules_2.GUIDE/noteoff}




Modules that affect the sequence of MIDI Events:
-----------------------------------------------

These modules are used to block specified events (or classes of events),
or to divert them onto another path for special treatment. All except the
first are `Filters', which select the events to be affected -- and will
block these from proceeding further along the path if this is what is
desired.  If a `split' is wanted -- rather than simply to discard the
events -- these filters are used in conjunction with the `Split Events'
module; in this case, the Filter simply marks the event, and a later Split
element diverts it onto the alternate path. (See the module descriptions.)
For more on `Marking' events, see @{" Marks " LINK mark_setting}.

  *   Split marked events to separate path
                                                          @{" Split Events  " LINK Modules_1.GUIDE/split}
  *   Filter out (block) or mark selected types of MIDI events
                                                          @{" Msg Filter    " LINK Modules_1.GUIDE/msg_f}
  *   Filter out or mark selected notes of the scale
                                                          @{" Key Filter    " LINK Modules_1.GUIDE/key_f}
  *   Pass a selected Keyboard note range -- filter or mark the rest
                                                          @{" Key Range     " LINK Modules_1.GUIDE/key_r}
  *   Filter out or mark selected MIDI Channels
                                                          @{" Chan Filter   " LINK Modules_2.GUIDE/chan_f}



MIDI Recording:
--------------

  *   Record and Play MIDI Sequences
                                                          @{" RePlay " LINK Modules_2.GUIDE/replay}


MIDIFile Handling:
-----------------

  *   Read a Sequence from a MIDI File
                                                        @{" Read MIDI File  " LINK Modules_MIDIFile.GUIDE/read_midi }



Miscellaneous Modules:
---------------------

  *   Block all `System' type MIDI events (hex code Fx)
                                                          @{" Block Sys Msg " LINK Modules_1.GUIDE/block_sys}
  *   Join up to three Web paths into one
                                                          @{" Join          " LINK Modules_1.GUIDE/join}
  *   Generate a delayed version of an incoming event stream
                                                          @{" Delay         " LINK Modules_1.GUIDE/delay}
  *   Play the amiga's audio as a MIDI instrument (using 8SVX voice)
                                                          @{" Instrument    " LINK Modules_1.GUIDE/instr}
  *   Monitor (display in a screen panel) events on a path
                                                          @{" Monitor MIDI  " LINK Modules_1.GUIDE/mon}
  *   Ensure proper sequencing of multiple Note-On/Note-Offs
                                                          @{" Serialize     " LINK Modules_2.GUIDE/serialize}

                          +  +  +
Control Panels
--------------

Element `Control Panels' are opened by clicking on the element while
in `Param' mode, or choosing `Param' from the `Select' mode panel
(see @{" Control Buttons " LINK Reference.GUIDE/buttons} in the Reference.GUIDE).  Each panel has a default
position in which it will appear (and will overlay other instances of the
same panel if not moved).  If you move it to a different part of the screen
it will remain there, even if closed and reopened.

                            +  +  +


Remember that each module is a separate program that must be run (normally
by the startup script) for the Web to be able to access it.  For more
information on the relation of Modules to the Web as a whole, please
refer to the main @{" Reference.GUIDE " LINK Reference.GUIDE/MAIN}.

  *   Some modules not shown in the buttons (MIDIBranch, FileReq, Load8SVX)
      should also be running:                         @{" Ancillary modules " LINK Modules_1.GUIDE/ancill}


              +  +  +  +  +  +  +  +  +  +  +  +  +  +


 Licensed Edition Modules
==========================

These modules are not supplied with this version, but documentation is
provided for completeness:


 Modules that modify MIDI Event parameters:
 -----------------------------------------

  *   Scale PitchBend or AfterTouch Values
                                                          @{" Scale PB/AT   " LINK Modules_2.GUIDE/ptscale }


 Modules that affect the sequence of MIDI Events:
 -----------------------------------------------

  *   Mark Note-On events above specified velocity
                                                          @{" Velocity Filt " LINK Modules_2.GUIDE/vel_f}


 Modules that process Control messages
 -------------------------------------

 @{" Control Messages " LINK MCTL} are not part of the MIDI protocol, but are rather
 a standardized feature of the Web that can provide control signals to
 elements independently of the data flowing around the system.  At the
 moment the MusicWeb only uses them to select particular paths for MIDI
 streams, but the future should hold much more.

  *   Switch paths according to Control Messages received
                                                          @{" MIDI Switcher " LINK Modules_1.GUIDE/switch}
  *   Generate Control Messages from MIDI Program Change events
                                                          @{" Prog Change   " LINK Modules_1.GUIDE/pchange}
  *   Generate Control Messages by panel button clicks
                                                          @{" Selector      " LINK Modules_1.GUIDE/select}
  *   Generate Control Messages from GamePort (Joystick) inputs
                                                          @{" Gameport Ctrl " LINK Modules_2.GUIDE/joycontrol}

 Note that these modules with a `Trigger' input will be triggered by
 Control Messages as well as by MIDI:
                                                          @{" RePlay        " LINK Modules_2.GUIDE/replay}
                                                          @{" Generate MIDI " LINK Modules_2.GUIDE/midi_gen}

 Other elements (currently) will simply pass them on and ignore them if
 they appear at their inputs.


 MIDIFile Handling:
 -----------------

  *   Write a Sequence to a MIDI File
                                                        @{" Write MIDI File " LINK Modules_MIDIFile.GUIDE/write_midi }


 MIDI Event Generation:
 ---------------------

  *   Generate arbitrary individual MIDI events
                                                          @{" Generate MIDI " LINK Modules_2.GUIDE/midi_gen}

                            +  +  +

@endnode

@node MCTL  "Control Messages"

 Control Messages
==================
                `Control Messages' are *not* part of the MIDI protocol:
                they are specific to the Web scheme.  They will normally
                -- but not necessarily -- be kept largely on separate
                paths from the MIDI event streams themselves.  There are
                various ways of generating them (and will be more). It
                is intended that their use will expand as time goes on.

                At the moment, most modules ignore Control Messages.
                Only the @{" MIDISwitch " LINK Modules_1.GUIDE/switch}  module responds to them, and has
                a separate `Control' input for this.  They can be
                generated by a couple of modules: @{" Selector " LINK Modules_1.GUIDE/select} generates
                them when a panel button is clicked, and @{" ProgChange " LINK Modules_1.GUIDE/pchange}
                does so when a MIDI program-change event is received.
                One other module is also included for those willing to
                do some simple wiring: @{" Gameport Control " LINK Modules_2.GUIDE/joycontrol} accepts
                GamePort signals to trigger Control Messages.

                Also note that `RePlay' and MIDIGen' have `Trigger' inputs
                that respond to any arrival, including Control Messages.

                Details of their format are unimportant at this stage,
                but for future reference you may like to know that they
                have a `type' and `value'.  Only the `Path Switch' type
                is implemented at the moment; these can in fact have a
                far wider value range than the 8 accepted by the current
                MIDISwitch module, but this should be enough to be
                going on with.  (In the descriptions of the relevant
                modules, the other possible types are ignored for now.)

@endnode


                               + + + + +

@node mark_setting "Setting `Marks' on MIDI Events"

    `Marks' are a feature of the MusicWeb: they are not part of standard
    MIDI.  They are tags that can be attached to any MIDI event passing
    along a MusicWeb path, to select that event for action further down
    the path.  Currently the only module that responds to marks is the
    `MIDI Split', which diverts marked events into an alternative path,
    but other actions may be added in the future.

    Marks can be set by any of the Filter elements that select events
    according to some criterion, such as Key Range or Message Type.
    There are four possible marks that may be affixed to an individual
    event.  A given filter may be set to tag events meeting its criterion
    with any one of these; a split element may be set to respond to any
    combination of the four.

    Currently a mark is only cleared when the event reaches a split
    element that is set to respond to it; marks not handled by that
    element are left alone.  (There is no way at the moment to
    `conditionally' clear a mark, though you could use dummy split
    elements suitably connected to do so.)

    Current modules that can set marks:
                                          @{"   Msg Filter    " LINK Modules_1.GUIDE/msg_f}
                                          @{"   Key Filter    " LINK Modules_1.GUIDE/key_f}
                                          @{"   Key Range     " LINK Modules_1.GUIDE/key_r}
                                          @{"   Chan Filter   " LINK Modules_2.GUIDE/chan_f}
                                          @{" Velocity Filter " LINK Modules_2.GUIDE/vel_f}

    Module that diverts marked events:
                                          @{"   Split Events  " LINK Modules_1.GUIDE/split}


@endnode

                               + + + + +
